    To write the required query based on the provided instructions, you can use PL/SQL with exception handling to manage the divide-by-zero error. Here's a query that will achieve this:
    BEGIN
      FOR rec IN (SELECT * FROM SALES_ORDER ORDER BY ORDER_NUMBER) LOOP
          IF rec.QUANTITY =  THEN
              DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(&#39;Wrong order quantity &#39;);
              EXIT;
          ELSE
              DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(rec.ORDER_NUMBER || &#39; &#39; || TO_CHAR(TO_DATE(rec.ORDER_DATE, &#39;DD-Mon-YY&#39;), &#39;DD-Mon-YYYY&#39;) || &#39; &#39; || rec.ITEM_NAME || &#39; &#39; || rec.AMOUNT || &#39; 1&#39; || rec.QUANTITY);
          END IF;
      END LOOP;
  EXCEPTION
      WHEN OTHERS THEN
          NULL; -- Do nothing on other exceptions.
  END;
  /
    Here’s what this code does:
    • Loops through each record of the SALES_ORDER table sorted by ORDER_NUMBER.
    • Checks if QUANTITY is zero and prints an error message "Wrong order quantity " before exiting.
    • If QUANTITY is not zero, it formats and outputs the details as specified.
    • Handles any other exceptions silently.
    Make sure to run this PL/SQL block in an environment that supports it, such as Oracle SQL Developer or any other tool with Oracle Database support.
